programme.title: World's Greatest: Mega Cities
programme.desc: Mega Cities provide a bustling home to populations of over 10 million. Travel from the high-density living of Shanghai and Bangkok to the sprawling cities of Delhi and Mexico City, each the backdrop for dynamic cultures.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Monuments & Landmarks
programme.desc: Many of the world’s most significant manmade wonders serve not as dwellings, but as powerful signposts. But more than giving us direction, they tell us a story - they characterize powerful forces, or commemorate power lost.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Archipelagos
programme.desc: The romantic notion of island life has always attracted us. Explore the histories, cultures, and unique ways of life on the World’s Greatest Archipelagos - clusters of islands that share common bonds of geography, geology, and genealogy.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Coasts
programme.desc: Along coasts, one element ends and another begins. No two days are ever the same on a coastline: the only thing that remains a constant is the timeless power of the sea.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Ancient Cities
programme.desc: In Ancient Cities, we journey to these ancestors of influence such as Luang Prabang, Vienna, and Istanbul where religious and cultural centers have shaped the ways in which we view the world around us and continue to do so in modern times.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Water Adventures
programme.desc: We are captivated by oceans, rivers, and lakes - the power, the flow, the reflective stillness. And as we seek to get closer, we immerse ourselves in an expanding range of aquatic experiences.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Drives
programme.desc: A journey by road expands our horizons, allowing us to explore the depth and breadth of whole countries and continents, stopping whenever and wherever we chose.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Global Cities
programme.desc: Travel to the centers of wealth, power, industry, and innovation. From London to Tokyo, Hong Kong to New York, these are the cities that never sleep. The influence held in these economic hubs unites the global community.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Island Nations
programme.desc: Though many are small in stature, they have punched well above their weight on the global stage. Some are rooted in ancient history, while others are only just beginning to realize their full potential.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Timeless Cities & Towns
programme.desc: These cities and towns are special places where the past coexists with the present, creating cultures totally unique to their people and their part of the world and adhering to ancient traditions and while introducing modern innovations.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Sacred Sites
programme.desc: Ancient in architecture and detailed in design, these man-made masterpieces stand as testaments to the strength of human faith. These sites endure as a timeless reminder of resilience, respect, and the need to reflect.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Marine Animals
programme.desc: From the surprises of colorful reef characters to effervescent penguins, killer sharks, and regal whales, dive into the places where nature reveals itself in some of its most marvelous and bizarre forms.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Nearshore Islands
programme.desc: Some of the world’s greatest islands are so close that they blend in with the mainland. But regardless of their size and origins, they are often the islands we are drawn to the most, each forging their own unique identity.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Mountains
programme.desc: The earth’s fragile crust has folded and faulted, and nowhere are these natural forces more evident than in the world’s great mountains. Explore the highest peaks of the world’s terrain - the rugged realm between heaven and earth.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Volcanoes
programme.desc: There are few sights on earth as compelling as a volcanic eruption. Volcanoes have the potential to cause death and widespread destruction in a heartbeat, but they also give rise to new life and ecosystems.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Volcanic Islands
programme.desc: They've been worshiped and feared over the millennia. But in the wake of drama and destruction, the elements give rise to cultures and nations so beautiful that we've come to know them as the world's greatest volcanic islands.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Grassland Animals
programme.desc: Grasslands are the great stages of the natural world where large animals play out spectacular lives in clear view of people, including lions, leopards, elephants, rhinoceros, cheetahs, impalas, kangaroos, wallaby, potoroo, bison, and wolves.

programme.title: War Story: Where Hell is: The Leopold and the Scheldt
programme.desc: The Allies liberated Antwerp, the world’s largest deep-water port, on 4 September 1944, but it could only be accessed via the Scheldt Estuary, the perfect place for the Germans to make a stand.
programme.sub-title: Where Hell is: The Leopold and the Scheldt

programme.title: War Story: Falaise, the corridor of death
programme.desc: The Canadian army played the pivotal role in closing the Falaise Gap and ensuring Allied victory in the Normandy Campaign in August 1944.

programme.title: War Story: D-Day plus 1
programme.desc: The Canadian stand against the 12th SS Panzer Division Hitlerjugend immediately after D-Day allowed the Allies to switch to the offensive and truly begin the liberation of Europe.

programme.title: War Story: Surviving Dieppe
programme.desc: The Dieppe assault of 19 August 1942 is the worst day in Canadian military history: in just 8 hours, 907 Canadians were killed. For 2,000 of their comrades, nearly three years of incarceration in German prison camps followed.

programme.title: War Story: Whistle for a Tiffy
programme.desc: From D-Day, Tactical Air Force fighter-bombers played a pivotal role in Allied battlefield success; Canadian soldiers knew they could always “whistle for a Tiffy”.

programme.title: War Story: Behind Enemy Lines
programme.desc: Royal Canadian Air Force bombing operations play a crucial role in disrupting German infrastructure ahead of the Normandy invasion of June 1944. In the process, dozens of Canadian airmen are forced to bail out over occupied Belgium and France.

programme.title: War Story: Not One Step Back: The Battle of Stalingrad
programme.desc: In the summer of 1942, the Germans advance to seize the rich oilfields of the Caucasus. In their path, the city of Stalingrad, its Soviet defenders personally ordered by Stalin to “take not one step back".
programme.sub-title: Not One Step Back: The Battle of Stalingrad

programme.title: War Story: Buchenwald Airmen
programme.desc: For two months in 1944, 168 Allied airmen were shot down over occupied France, betrayed to the Gestapo by the same collaborator, transported to the Nazi concentration and slave labour camp Buchenwald.

programme.title: War Story: The Last Ship: The Sinking of the Esquimalt
programme.desc: On 16 April 1945, a mere three weeks before German surrender, the submarine fired a single torpedo that sank the last Canadian naval vessel lost to enemy action.
programme.sub-title: The Last Ship: The Sinking of the Esquimalt

programme.title: War Story: Prisoners of the Sun
programme.desc: On 16 November 1941, two Canadian battalions arrived in the British colony of Hong Kong. Their aim: Bolster the Empire’s defenses in the event of aggression by the restless forces of Japan, stationed only kilometres away in occupied China.

programme.title: War Story: Vengeance
programme.desc: In 1941, nearly 30,000 Jews escaped the ghettos and work camps and they joined the growing underground resistance army, actively fighting the Nazis.

programme.title: War Story: Across the Rhine: Paras in Germany
programme.desc: In mid-September 1944, the remnants of the battered 1st Canadian Parachute Battalion participated in the largest parachute drop in history, fought a successful battle.
programme.sub-title: Across the Rhine: Paras in Germany

programme.title: War Story: Out of the Clouds: Paras in Normandy
programme.desc: In Normandy, the 1st Canadian Parachute Battalion proved itself to be in the vanguard of the best-trained and toughest units in the Allied forces.
programme.sub-title: Out of the Clouds: Paras in Normandy

programme.title: War Story: The Road to Rome
programme.desc: The Road to Rome examines the incredible experiences of Canadian veterans, the victories and horrors of armoured combat, and the pivotal value, far too often neglected, of the overall Italian Campaign.

programme.title: War Story: Ortona: The War Inside
programme.desc: The War Inside is a personal retelling of one of the fiercest battles of the Italian Campaign from the searing points of view of Canadian infantrymen, a tanker, a stretcher bearer, and a German paratrooper.

programme.title: War Story: Sicily: The First Campaign
programme.desc: The Sicily Campaign began with the largest seaborne invasion in history on 9-10 July 1943. The Allied forces of Britain, Canada, and the United States sought to knock Italy out of the war and attack Germany from the south.

programme.title: War Story: Bomb Girls Remember
programme.desc: During the Second World War, 250,000 Canadian women helped to build the arsenal of democracy. These young women met the challenges of factory work and helped to win the Second World War, and by doing so, paved the way for future generations.

programme.title: War Story: Bomber Command: Getting Home
programme.desc: In this film, Bomber Command personnel and a Luftwaffe pilot take the viewer through the frightening reality of fighting in the skies as they try to get a damaged bomber home.

programme.title: War Story: Bomber Command: Hitting Back
programme.desc: After surviving the German bombing campaign of British cities, RAF Bomber Command struck back against Germany. The devastating consequences of raids, for both for the young men in the skies and the people on the ground, are portrayed in this film.

programme.title: NEW: World War II in HD Colour
programme.desc: Japan continues its suicidal resistance, and invading it looks costly. After 2 atomic bombs, the Emperor intervenes and stops the War. Stalin grabs territory in East Asia. The War is over, and the Atomic Era and the Cold War start.

programme.title: NEW: World War II in HD Colour
programme.desc: In 1945, Germany is crumbly on both fronts. The Western Allies cross the Rhine and take most of Germany, while the Red Army quickly advances into Berlin. After Hitler's suicide, Germany surrenders and is divided among the allied powers.

programme.title: NEW: World War II in HD Colour
programme.desc: The Marines succeed in the "island hopping" strategy against suicidal resistance. The US Navy establishes supremacy, cutting off Japan.

programme.title: NEW: World War II in HD Colour
programme.desc: The Western Allies secure supply routes that will allow them to enter Germany, and the Ardennes counter-offensive fails. The Red Army advances rapidly. The SS implements the Holocaust.

programme.title: NEW: World War II in HD Colour
programme.desc: After a careful campaign of disinformation that throws the German defenders off-guard, the Western Allies finally land on Normandy.France is liberated.

programme.title: NEW: World War II in HD Colour
programme.desc: Their attack on the Soviet Union having failed, the German Army suffers a series of counter-offensives on the Eastern Front. Wehrmacht's losses are huge as the Soviets advance West.

programme.title: NEW: World War II in HD Colour
programme.desc: Allies turn the tide in the Atlantic, where initially German U-Boats harass freely convoys to supply Britain. The route to bring American soldiers who will land on D-Day is clear.

programme.title: NEW: World War II in HD Colour
programme.desc: Italy's failed attacks in the Mediterranean region draw in the Germans.

programme.title: NEW: World War II in HD Colour
programme.desc: Japan attacks the USA on 7 Dec 1941. For the next 6 months, they continue to have successful attacks.

programme.title: The Abyss: Rise And Fall of The Nazis: The Seeds of Violence 1918-1922
programme.desc: The Seeds of Violence 1918-1922: In the wake of the First World War, Adolf Hitler identifies Benito Mussolini as his model and has one ultimate goal: to gain power in Germany.

programme.title: The Abyss: Rise And Fall of The Nazis: Deceit and Delusion 1923-1928
programme.desc: Deceit and Delusion 1923-1928: Hitler appears to be eliminated after his failed putsch in 1923. Discover how the Nazi movement used democracy's tolerance in Germany to come back.

programme.title: The Abyss: Rise And Fall of The Nazis: Democracy without Democrats 1929-1933
programme.desc: Democracy Without Democrats 1929-1933: A protest turns into a racist and anti-Jewish movement during the 1920s and the NSDAP use emotions to gain the loyalty of the people.

programme.title: The Abyss: Rise And Fall of The Nazis: The Racial State 1933-1934
programme.desc: The Racial State 1933-1934: President Hindenburg suspends freedom of speech and Hitler comes to power in 1933. The first concentration camps for political opponents are set up.

programme.title: The Abyss: Rise And Fall of The Nazis: Hidden in Plain Sight 1935-1938
programme.desc: Hidden In Plain Sight 1935-1938: In 1934, Hitler's government is firmly in the saddle. Most Germans support Hitler's anti-Jewish policy and the regime's terror soon escalates.

programme.title: The Abyss: Rise And Fall of The Nazis: Up in Flames 1936-1940
programme.desc: Up in Flames 1936-1940: At the end of 1939, the German Army invades Poland. Examine how Hitler succeeded in pushing through his rearmament and war plans relatively unhindered.

programme.title: The Abyss: Rise And Fall of The Nazis: The Gates of Hell 1941-1942
programme.desc: The Gates of Hell 1941-1942: In the shadow of the war, the Nazi regime gradually advances its "final solution to the Jewish problem", culminating in the Holocaust.

programme.title: The Abyss: Rise And Fall of The Nazis: Genocide 1942-1944
programme.desc: Genocide 1942 - 1944: Along with Treblinka and Majdanek, Sobibor was one of the camps used in Operation Reinhard, in which the Nazis murdered almost two million people.

programme.title: The Abyss: Rise And Fall of The Nazis: Armageddon 1943-1945
programme.desc: Armageddon 1943-1945: The defeat at Stalingrad in 1943 was the turning point of the war and convinced the Nazi leadership to intensify their terror and propaganda campaigns.

programme.title: The Abyss: Rise And Fall of The Nazis: The Reckoning 1945-1948
programme.desc: The Reckoning 1945-1948: In 1945, WWII was over but the violence had not ended. The survivors want to blame the Germans. The reckoning with National Socialism is ambivalent.

programme.title: Bomber: Terror of WWII: Rise of The Bomber
programme.desc: Rise of the Bomber: The story of a deadly war that intertwines Germany, Poland, Japan, Italy and Spain as the remorseless development of weapons and bombers.

programme.title: Bomber: Terror of WWII: War Without Boundaries
programme.desc: War Without Boundaries: The story of a deadly war that intertwines Germany, Poland, Japan, Italy and Spain as the remorseless development of weapons and bombers.

programme.desc: This first episode provides context for when, how and why the mobile death squads, or EZG, were established.

programme.desc: In December 1941, after the EZG’s intervention, Romania, Bulgaria, Hungary and the Baltic states are declared 'Judenfrei': free of Jews.

programme.title: Goddess Remembered
programme.desc: This poetic documentary is a salute to 35 000 years of "pre-history," to the values of ancestors only recently remembered, and to the goddess-worshipping religions of the ancient past.

programme.title: The Street
programme.desc: A poignant adaptation of Mordecai Richler's short story candidly depicts families' responses to aging members. Through watercolor and ink, the filmmaker captures raw family emotions, reflecting harsh realities.

programme.title: Strings
programme.desc: Strings: a haunting film of intimate strangers linked by shared spaces. Comfortable connections fracture when a problem arises. Created with glass painting and stop-motion, it's visually stunning.

programme.title: The Sweater
programme.desc: Roch Carrier narrates a childhood mishap in "The Hockey Sweater." In rural Quebec, boys idolize Maurice "Rocket" Richard. When the protagonist receives a Toronto Maple Leafs jersey instead of a Canadiens one, embarrassment ensues at the local rink.

programme.title: How They Saw Us Is It A Womans World
programme.desc: This film, made especially for television in 1956, embodies the conventional myth that women indirectly exercise power through their ability to manipulate men through sex and marriage.

programme.title: A Mother And Daughter On Abortion
programme.desc: The document of an intimate conversation between a mother and her adult daughter. They speak candidly about their personal experiences in trying to obtain an abortion, and how, in different decade, each got caught up in the system and its rules.

programme.title: Perfecting The Art Of Longing
programme.desc: Using footage from security cameras, video calls and home-video archives, this experimental short film leads us on a journey through memory, family and faith, exploring the nature of connection and distance.

programme.title: Sunrise Over Tiananmen Square
programme.desc: Shui-Bo Wang's animated documentary intertwines personal journey with history, exploring China's '60s-'80s upheavals. From symbol of hope to tragedy, it depicts Wang's roles from Red Guard to teacher, exploring idealism and intolerance.

programme.title: If You Love This Planet
programme.desc: This film records a lecture given to students by outspoken nuclear critic, Dr. Helen Caldicott, president of Physicians for Social Responsibility in the United States. Her message is clear: disarmament cannot be postponed.

programme.title: Chaque Enfant
programme.desc: This is the story of a baby who appears mysteriously on the doorstep of a busy executive, and who is subsequently bounced from household to household down the block. Nobody in the community is interested in caring for the baby without a name.

programme.title: Notmans World
programme.desc: William Notman was a man of rare talent. Photography was still in its infancy when he opened his first studio--in Montréal--in the late 1850s. He rapidly turned his art, and a budding technology, into a highly successful business.

programme.title: Mary Two-Axe Earley I Am Indian Again
programme.desc: This film shares the powerful story of Mary Two-Axe Earley, who fought for more than two decades to challenge sex discrimination against First Nations women embedded in Canada’s Indian Act and became a key figure in Canada’s women’s rights movement.

programme.title: The Secret Order
programme.desc: Phil Comeau shines a spotlight on the Ordre de Jacques-Cartier and paints a gripping portrait of the social and political struggles of Canadian francophone-minority communities.

programme.title: Canada Vignettes Log Drivers Waltz
programme.desc: A young girl who loves to dance and is ready to marry chooses a log driver over his more well-to-do, land-loving competition. Driving logs down the river has made him the best dancing partner to be found.

programme.title: The Man Who Stole Dreams
programme.desc: This enchanting and magical animation film, an ode to our dreams during the night, celebrates the creative imagination, uniqueness, and the human spirit. The plot involves a man who steals the dreams of villagers, the tries to sell them back to the them.

programme.title: Tu As Crie Let Me Go
programme.desc: In "Tu as crié LET ME GO," Anne Claire Poirier explores her daughter's tragic descent into drugs and prostitution, seeking understanding of the societal pressures influencing young people's risky behaviors in Montreal's streets.

programme.title: Best Time Of My Life Portraits Of Women In Mid-Life, The
programme.desc: An upbeat, positive film about a group of women dealing with mid-life and menopause. The women come from a wide range of backgrounds, careers and lifestyles, it effectively dispels popular myths and fears about life during and after menopause.

programme.title: Gurdeep Singh Bains
programme.desc: Gurdeep is a thirteen-year-old Canadian Sikh whose family runs a dairy farm near Chilliwack, British Columbia. They have retained their language and religion. Sometimes he feels a little different from the other children because he wears a turban.

programme.title: Le Grand Serpent Du Monde
programme.desc: A young forty-something, Tom Paradise refuses to grow up. Behind the wheel of his bus he drives endlessly through the city, tracing out the path of his life, dreaming of the landscape of the American West that forever impressed him

programme.title: Challenger An Industrial Romance
programme.desc: Follows the development of Canadair's super-executive jet. The film captures the spirit of the Canadian air transport industry and its attempt to compete with the American leaders in the industry.

programme.title: Waiting
programme.desc: The patient Dinkas of South Sudan endure famine amid civil strife. Aid arrives in Alek, but distribution is delayed to prevent unrest, revealing the stark reality of hunger.

programme.title: Benoit
programme.desc: Benoît is an astonishingly accomplished eleven-year-old Québécois from Joliette. He pursues such diverse activities as weight lifting and playing the violin.

programme.title: Very Nice Very Nice
programme.desc: Arthur Lipsett's debut film peels back life's facade, revealing hidden anxieties beneath. Through familiar images and fragmented speech, it critiques societal norms, punctuated by the recurring phrase, "Very nice, very nice.

programme.title: Ill Find A Way
programme.desc: When nine-year-old Nadia is allowed to attend a regular school, she knows the kids will tease her but she'll "find a way to deal with it." Nadia has spina bifida, a congenital condition that has caused a lack of sensation from the knees down.

programme.title: Mother Earth/La Terre Notre Mere
programme.desc: Mother Earth is a short, evocative, poetic film that celebrates life on our planet. This documentary film looks at the reality of human beings; the earth is our home and we are profoundly connected to all other beings.

programme.title: Sea Dream
programme.desc: Children, like adults, have days that go wrong. This film shows how one little girl overcomes the day's frustrations by diving into an underwater fantasy where she spends time with her friend, the lady octopus.

programme.title: Danish Poet, The
programme.desc: Can we trace the chain of events that leads to our own birth? Is our existence just coincidence? The Danish Poet considers these questions as we follow a poet whose creative well has run dry, on a holiday to Norway to meet a famous writer.

programme.title: How They Saw Us Wings On Her Shoulder
programme.desc: This is a 1943 recruitment film. Although it specifically promises women jobs in post-war aviation, its primary message is that women fulfill support positions "so that men might fly.

programme.title: King Of The Hill
programme.desc: Spring 1972. The Chicago Cubs are poised to win the National League's Pennant race, lead by their star pitcher, a Black Canadian named Ferguson Jenkins, who was inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame in 1991. This is his story.

programme.title: Unsere Wilde Schweiz, Staffel 2
programme.desc: Inmitten von himmlisch schönen Bergeshöhen thront der Piz Beverin über dem Naturpark, dem er seinen Namen verleiht. Zu seinen Füßen erstreckt sich eine Landschaft voller wilder Natur. Tiefe Schluchten und glasklare Bergseen, artenreiche Trockenwiesen und seltene Moore, majestätische Steinböcke und zurückkehrende Wölfe.

programme.title: Unsere Wilde Schweiz, Staffel 2
programme.desc: Unendliche Wälder, eine herbe, unversehrte Natur und launisches Wetter prägen den Naturpark Waadtländer Jura. Wer einmal dort war, weiß um seinen besonderen Reiz: den der Abgeschiedenheit. Mit seinen Seen, Wäldern und von Trockenmauern geprägten Weiden steht das Naturjuwel für das ewige Zusammenspiel von Mensch und Natur. Das Grenzgebiet zu Frankreich bedeckt der riesige Risoud-Wald.

programme.title: DIE HALBINSEL
programme.desc: Einer der symbolträchtigsten Lebensräume der iberischen Halbinsel ist der Mittelmeerwald, das Land des Iberischen Luchses, einer einzigartigen und faszinierenden Raubkatze mit einer Erfolgsgeschichte bei der Erhaltung der Tiere. Korkeichen und Steineichen sind die Herren dieser herrlichen Wälder. Und diese Wälder beherbergen eine einzigartige und endemische Fauna. Damit ist diese Region einer der wichtigsten Biodiversitäts-Hotspots der Erde.

programme.title: DIE HALBINSEL
programme.desc: Berge sind für die gesamte Morphologie Iberiens verantwortlich. Sie sind auch der Geburtsort der Flüsse, die das Leben im gesamten Gebiet verteilen. Hier gibt es viele Wälder, jeder mit seinem eigenen Ökosystem. Iberische Gebirgsketten haben unterschiedliche Gesichter und Persönlichkeiten, ebenso wie ihre wilden Bewohner.

programme.title: DIE HALBINSEL
programme.desc: Die Küste der Iberischen Halbinsel trifft sowohl auf den Atlantischen Ozean als auch auf das Mittelmeer. Es ist einer der reichsten ozeanischen Lebensräume Europas. Es beherbergt Tausende von Wildtierarten. Entlang der 3000 km² großen Küste finden wir schroffe Klippen, Dünensysteme und ausgedehnte Sandstrände, Flussmündungen und Marschland. Alle diese Landschaften sind ein geologisches Zeugnis der Vergangenheit der Halbinsel und jede von ihnen beherbergt unterschiedliche Lebensformen, die zum Gleichgewicht der natürlichen Welt beitragen.

programme.title: Asiens tödlichste Schlangen
programme.desc: Der Giftforscher Bryan Fry durchreist ganz Asien von den Laboratorien in Singapur bis in den Dschungel von Indien auf der Suche nach Giftschlangen mit dem Ziel, den perfekten Killer in Asien zu identifizieren.

programme.title: Cordóba, die Stadt der Patios
programme.desc: Planet Weltweit: Der ganze Stolz von Córdoba sind die Patios der Stadt - begrünte Innenhöfe, deren Wurzeln bis in die römische Antike und die Zeit der maurischen Herrschaft in Andalusien zurückreichen. Einmal im Jahr findet ein traditioneller Wettbewerb statt. Dann dreht sich alles um die Frage: Wer hat den schönsten Patio der ganzen Stadt?

programme.title: Kourou: Palmen, Raketen, Gefängnisinseln
programme.desc: Planet Weltweit: Lange war Französisch-Guayana an der Küste Südamerikas ein Schreckensort für Gefangene. Die Zuchthäuser dort galten als die härtesten Frankreichs. Heute sind von ihnen nur noch Ruinen übrig, die restauriert werden. Frankreich beginnt, dieses dunkle Kapitel seiner Geschichte aufzuarbeiten, nur einige Kilometer entfernt vom Weltraumbahnhof Kourou.

programme.title: Die Minenratten von Tansania
programme.desc: Im Forschungszentrum der Organisation APOPO in Tansania herrscht helle Aufregung: Eine Rattenmutter hat Junge geworfen - ein Riesenerfolg bei in Gefangenschaft lebenden Riesenhamsterratten. Schnell zeigt sich, dass einer der Rattenjungen besonders aufgeweckt ist. Er bekommt den Namen Ronaldinho. In nur wenigen Wochen lernt das intelligente Tier gefährliches TNT zu erschnüffeln.

programme.title: Montenegro
programme.desc: Planet Weltweit: Noch vor wenigen Jahren waren Esel in Montenegro vom Aussterben bedroht. Dass es die treuen Helfer noch immer gibt, ist vor allem Darko Savelji¿ zu verdanken. 2015 rettete der Biologe die erste, in elenden Verhältnissen gehaltene Eselstute. Kurze Zeit später nahm er zwei andere Esel zu sich, die als Futter für Jagdhunde geschlachtet werden sollten.

programme.title: Zuflucht in den Anden
programme.desc: Planet Weltweit: Am Tag arbeiten sie hart wie Männer. Am Abend verwandeln sie sich in das, als was sie sich fühlen: in Frauen. In ihren Gemeinden wurden sie verachtet und verstoßen. Auf den Kaffeeplantagen der kolumbianischen Anden, haben sie ein Refugium gefunden. Die Gemeinschaft von Transfrauen muss bis heute um ihre Anerkennung kämpfen

programme.title: Die Schweizergarde
programme.desc: Planet Weltweit: Seit 1506 schützt die Schweizergarde den Papst und seine Residenz. Verändert haben sich jedoch die Methoden und das Umfeld der Elitetruppe. In der traditionellen Renaissance-Uniform steckt heute ein junger, moderner und gut ausgebildeter Schweizer, der bereit ist, sein Leben für die Sicherheit des Papstes zu geben.

programme.title: Die Sonnenmenschen von Tokelau
programme.desc: Drei einsame Atolle mitten im Pazifik, die zu Pionieren in Sachen Energieerzeugung wurden: Tokelau ist die erste Nation der Welt, die ihre Stromproduktion zu 100 Prozent auf Solarenergie umgestellt hat.

programme.title: Indien
programme.desc: Planet Weltweit: Indien, das Land der Spiritualität. Heiler und Gurus, sogenannte Babas, berufen sich auf höhere Mächte. Doch es gibt Widerstand gegen den gefährlichen Aberglauben und die Geschäftemacherei mit der oft verzweifelten Hoffnung auf Gesundheit. Rationalisten touren mit ihrem Science-Van im Dienst der Wissenschaft durch das Land und klären auf.

programme.title: Ray Charles & The Raelettes
programme.sub-title: Ray Charles and the Raelettes - North Sea Jazz
programme.desc: The North Sea Jazz Festival is the largest indoor music festival in the world, known globally as the event where the past, present and future of jazz are featured within three days. Next to a firm base of jazz as the festival's staple music genre, many others, such as blues, soul, funk, or hip hop, pass by. In 1980, American soul legend Ray Charles brought the Raelettes and the Ray Charles Orchestra to the North Sea Jazz Festival in The Hague. With the full force of these two groups behind him, Charles showed why throughout his storied career he has been viewed as one of the most recognizable voices in music.

programme.title: Elizabeth Shepherd
programme.desc: An extraordinary collection of clips in all jazz genres from the most beautiful concerts and the most special festivals, performed by the finest jazz musicians.

programme.title: Oscar Peterson Trio, Stuff Smith & Ella Fitzgerald
programme.sub-title: O.P. Trio and E. Fitz. - Jazz At The Philharmonic
programme.desc: The Royal Concertgebouw in Amsterdam is a world-renowned concert hall, known for its first-rate acoustics. It has attracted many famous performers over the years and is one of the Netherlands' most treasured musical institutions. On May 5, 1957, jazz impresario Norman Granz presented his Jazz at the Philharmonic tour at the Concertgebouw in Amsterdam. The Canadian pianist Oscar Peterson and his trio of guitarist Herb Ellis and bassist Ray Brown are later joined by trumpeter Roy Eldridge and drummer Jo Jones. As an added attraction, American violinist Stuff Smith joins the proceedings. American singer Ella Fitzgerald, accompanied by pianist Don Abney, Ellis, Brown and Jones, hits her vocal peak in a stunning set that culminates in a jam session of It Don't Mean A Thing (If It Ain't Got That Swing) with the entire ensemble.

programme.title: Charlie Galbraith
programme.desc: An extraordinary collection of clips in all jazz genres from the most beautiful concerts and the most special festivals, performed by the finest jazz musicians.

programme.title: Steve Gadd
programme.desc: Many of pianist Chick Corea's compositions have become jazz standards. As a member of Miles Davis' band in the late 1960s, he participated in the birth of the electric jazz fusion movement. In the 1970s, Corea founded the legendary jazz fusion group Return to Forever. Along with Herbie Hancock, McCoy Tyner and Keith Jarrett, Corea is one of the biggest modern jazz pianists. He continued musical collaborations with a diverse range of artists, exploring various musical styles. This broadcast features three performances that illustrate Chick Corea's many talents.

programme.title: Miles Davis
programme.desc: American trumpeter Miles Davis (1926-1991) was a pioneering jazz musician from the late 1940s to the late 1980s. His influence on 20th century music is hard to overstate, as he trailblazed bebop, cool jazz, hardbop, modal jazz, and electronic music. On October 11, 1964, Miles Davis performed at Teatro Dell'Arte in Milan. With tenor saxophonist Wayne Shorter, pianist Herbie Hancock, bassist Ron Carter and drummer Tony Williams, Davis performed Autumn Leaves, My Funny Valentine, All Blues, All of You, and Joshua.

programme.title: Art Farmer, Jim Hall, Steve Swallow & Pete La Roca
programme.sub-title: The Art Farmer Quartet live In England
programme.desc: Art Farmer: Live in '64 highlights an amazing one-hour concert featuring the great flugelhornist in his prime. Farmer's band includes legendary guitarist Jim Hall (fresh from Sonny Rollins' band), drummer Pete LaRoca, and Steve Swallow on bass. The legendary ensemble plays both standards and originals with ease and finesse and highlights why Farmer was considered one of the most innovative horn players in all of jazz.

programme.title: New York Hip Hop
programme.desc: New York Hip Hop is a regional subgenre of hip hop music that originated in New York City during the 1970s and recognized to have evolved first in the Bronx New York hip hop became a distinct subgenre after artists from other regions of the United States emerged with different styles. In contrast to other styles, this used complex lyrics for attentive listening rather than beats for dancing. The main components of hip hop culture from that time and still today are MCing, DJing, break dancing, and graffiti. With Public Enemy, Ice Cube and Big Daddy Kane

Enjoy the biggest hits of the decade's most important artist: "Because You Loved Me", "All By Myself", "My Heart Will Go On", "I Drove All Night" and others!

programme.title: John Legend
programme.desc: An artist with intellectual skills is John Legend, who studied English with a major in African American literature at the University of Pennsylvania. In college, he participated in a jazz group called Counterparts and at the time was introduced to singer Lauryn Hill, playing piano on the track 'Everything Is Everything' from the singer's first solo album. He finished college in 1999 and began composing his own songs Recorded two independent albums that were sold in their performances: 'John Stephens' (2000) and 'Live at Jimmy Uptown' (2001). He has performed on albums of singers like Alicia Key, Jay-Z and also made the album Wake Up! (2010) along with the American rap group, The Roots. His official discography includes Get Lifted (2004), Once Again (2006), Evolver (2008) and Love in the Future (2013). This presentation in London, 2014, at the Itunes Festival, manages to clean the career of this singer who besides being multitalented can be a human rights activist.

programme.title: Funk
programme.desc: Funk is about the groove Funk is about the beat. Without the drums, without the bass, there is no Funk. Previously, Rock and Roll would put the beat on the two and the four, but by putting it on the one, changes the sound of the music and the rhythm of the music, and that really becomes the basis of what Funk is. James Brown is the originator of Funk. You have a guy who came out of R&B music, and he did something which hadn't really been done before, where he changed the rhythm.

programme.title: New York Hip Hop
programme.desc: New York Hip Hop is a regional subgenre of hip hop music that originated in New York City during the 1970s and recognized to have evolved first in the Bronx New York hip hop became a distinct subgenre after artists from other regions of the United States emerged with different styles. In contrast to other styles, this used complex lyrics for attentive listening rather than beats for dancing. The main components of hip hop culture from that time and still today are MCing, DJing, break dancing, and graffiti. With Public Enemy, Ice Cube and Big Daddy Kane

programme.title: Quatuor Ebène
programme.desc: Renowned French string quartet Quatuor Ébène marked the 250th birth anniversary of Ludwig van Beethoven (1770-1827) with a remarkable project: recording all of the great composer's sixteen string quartets. For five years, violinists Pierre Colombet and Gabriel Le Magadure, violist Marie Chilemme, and cellist Raphaël Merlin immersed themselves in Beethoven's 650 pages of sheet music. Their efforts culminated in the performance of the composer's complete repertoire for string quartet, which covers three decades of Beethoven's musical creativity, during six impressive concerts at Philharmonie de Paris in the autumn of 2020. Quatuor Ébène explored every facet of Beethoven's string quartet repertoire: from the youthful Opus 18 string quartets to the Razumovsky, Harp, and Serioso quartets (Opus 59, 74, and 95) from his middle period, and finally, the depth of his late quartets (Opus 127 to 135). This program features Quatuor Ébène performing Beethoven's String Quartet No. 3 in D major, Op. 18 No. 3 String Quartet No. 11 in F minor, Op. 95, “Quartetto Serioso” and String Quartet No. 8 in E minor, Op. 59, No. 2, "Razumovsky". This concert performance was recorded at Philharmonie de Paris on November 23, 2020.

programme.title: Matthias Goerne, Vilde Frang, Nicolas Altstaedt & Stathis Karapanos
programme.sub-title: J. S. Bach - Arias, solos, and duets
programme.desc: Baritone Matthias Goerne teams up with violinist Vilde Frang, cellist Nicolas Altstaedt, flutist Stathis Karapanos, and harpsichordist Michaela Hasselt in this program dedicated to the music of J. S. Bach. They perform baritone arias from Bach's most beautiful cantatas, as well as solo pieces and duets. On the program are Sonata No. 3 in C major for violin solo, BWV 1005 arias ‘Hier, in meines Vaters Stätte', BWV 32 and ‘Die Welt mit allen Königreichen', BWV 59 Suite No. 5 in C minor for cello solo, BWV 1011 ‘Wenn Trost und Hülf ermangeln muß', BWV 117 ‘Ja, ja, ich halte Jesum fest', BWV 157 Invention No. 7 in E minor, BWV 778 Invention in A major, BWV 783 and ‘Welt ade, ich bin dein müde', BWV 158. This performance was recorded at St. Mary's Church in Wittenberg, Germany.

programme.title: Elena Bashkirova, Juliane Banse, Emmanuel Pahud & Claudio Bohorquez
programme.desc: The extraordinarily talented pianist Elena Bashkirova has been president of the Felix Mendelssohn-Bartholdy Foundation in Leipzig since October 2020, succeeding legendary conductor Kurt Masur. In this concert at the Mendelssohn House in Leipzig, Bashkirova is joined by soprano Juliane Banse, flutist Emmanuel Pahud, cellist Claudio Bohórquez, clarinettist Karl-Heinz Steffens, and pianist Ohad Ben-Ari in a chamber music program dedicated to the music of Mendelssohn and his sister Fanny Hensel. The program opens with Mendelssohn's Piano Trio in D minor, Op. 49. This is followed by a selection of songs: Mendelssohn's Schilflied ‘Auf dem Teich, dem regungslosen', Op. 71 No. 4, and Reiselied ‘Der Herbstwind rüttelt die Bäume', Op. 34 No. 6 Hensel's Vorwurf, Op. 10 No. 2 Verlust, Op. 9 No. 10 and Sehnsucht, Op. 9 No. 7 Mendelssohn's ‘Allnächtlich im Traume seh ich dich', Op. 86 No. 4 ‘Die Liebende schreibt', Op. 86 No. 3 and Nachtlied ‘Vergangen ist der lichte Tag', Op. 71 No. 6. The program continues with Mendelssohn's Seven Songs without Words, for piano four-hands (Op. 62 Nos. 1-6, and Op. 67 No. 1), and comes to a close with Mendelssohn's Three pieces for clarinet, violoncello and piano (arr. Ernst Naumann), comprising Prelude, Op. 35 No. 4, Songs without Words, Op. 53 No. 2, and Duet, Op. 38 No. 6. This performance was recorded in November 2020.

programme.title: Costanza Principe
programme.desc: Italian classical pianist Costanza Principe (1993) started playing the piano at age 6, making her public debut at age 7. Before long she would be performing as a soloist with numerous prestigious orchestras in Italy, the UK, France, and South America. Seen here in 2021 at one of Italy's oldest extant Renaissance theatres, the gorgeous Teatro Olimpico in the northern Italian town of Vicenza, Principe performs Johann Sebastian Bach's ‘Concerto italiano' and ‘Ciaccona', as transcribed for piano by Ferruccio Busoni.

programme.title: Les Dissonances & David Grimal
programme.sub-title: Schubert - Symphony No. 8 in B minor, D. 759
programme.desc: Les Dissonances is a collective of artists founded by violinist David Grimal in 2004. The conductorless ensemble consists of musicians from the most prestigious European orchestras, international soloists, and young talents. In this performance Les Dissonances perform Franz Schubert's Symphony No. 8 in B minor, D. 759, also known as the ‘Unfinished Symphony'. Schubert started composing the work in 1822, but only completed the first two movements. The first movement, Allegro moderato, has a dark, mysterious mood, which contrasts with the beautiful second movement in E major, Andante con moto. Schubert only penned a couple of measures of the third movement, a Scherzo, in full score. It is not known why the composer never finished his symphony. Although it is not complete, it has become one of Schubert's most popular compositions. This performance was recorded at Cité de la musique in Paris, France, in 2013.

programme.title: Rainbow Reef Relaxation 1
programme.desc: Sit back, relax and enjoy the dazzling world of coral reefs in 4K you embark on a journey through some of the most vibrant underwater reefs on our blue planet - including many scenes which no longer look like this due to coral bleaching. From the cinematographer: "The footage for this film was shot over a period of some years in French Polynesia, Micronesia, Indonesia and East Timor. Unfortunately there are not that vibrant anymore today. Coral reefs have suffered from the rise of water temperature, rise in acidity, destructive fishing methods and severe storms caused by climate change." - Peter Schneider. "Rainbow Reef Relaxation" is a 3-hour long, sweeping yet majestic & vibrant underwater journey to the world's most beautiful lagoons, as captured by Nature Relaxation collaborator Peter Schneider (Underwatercam) paired with ambient underwater sounds and brand new ambient music by the Cynic Project. Filmed in High Definition several years ago, thanks to its age this film offers magical glimpses of an underwater world that is bursting with life, color, and beauty.

programme.title: Above the Fiji Islands II

programme.title: Unsere Wilde Schweiz, Staffel 2
programme.desc: Inmitten von himmlisch schönen Bergeshöhen thront der Piz Beverin über dem Naturpark, dem er seinen Namen verleiht. Zu seinen Füßen erstreckt sich eine Landschaft voller wilder Natur. Tiefe Schluchten und glasklare Bergseen, artenreiche Trockenwiesen und seltene Moore, majestätische Steinböcke und zurückkehrende Wölfe.

programme.title: Unsere Wilde Schweiz, Staffel 2
programme.desc: Unendliche Wälder, eine herbe, unversehrte Natur und launisches Wetter prägen den Naturpark Waadtländer Jura. Wer einmal dort war, weiß um seinen besonderen Reiz: den der Abgeschiedenheit. Mit seinen Seen, Wäldern und von Trockenmauern geprägten Weiden steht das Naturjuwel für das ewige Zusammenspiel von Mensch und Natur. Das Grenzgebiet zu Frankreich bedeckt der riesige Risoud-Wald.

programme.title: DIE HALBINSEL
programme.desc: Einer der symbolträchtigsten Lebensräume der iberischen Halbinsel ist der Mittelmeerwald, das Land des Iberischen Luchses, einer einzigartigen und faszinierenden Raubkatze mit einer Erfolgsgeschichte bei der Erhaltung der Tiere. Korkeichen und Steineichen sind die Herren dieser herrlichen Wälder. Und diese Wälder beherbergen eine einzigartige und endemische Fauna. Damit ist diese Region einer der wichtigsten Biodiversitäts-Hotspots der Erde.

programme.title: DIE HALBINSEL
programme.desc: Berge sind für die gesamte Morphologie Iberiens verantwortlich. Sie sind auch der Geburtsort der Flüsse, die das Leben im gesamten Gebiet verteilen. Hier gibt es viele Wälder, jeder mit seinem eigenen Ökosystem. Iberische Gebirgsketten haben unterschiedliche Gesichter und Persönlichkeiten, ebenso wie ihre wilden Bewohner.

programme.title: DIE HALBINSEL
programme.desc: Die Küste der Iberischen Halbinsel trifft sowohl auf den Atlantischen Ozean als auch auf das Mittelmeer. Es ist einer der reichsten ozeanischen Lebensräume Europas. Es beherbergt Tausende von Wildtierarten. Entlang der 3000 km² großen Küste finden wir schroffe Klippen, Dünensysteme und ausgedehnte Sandstrände, Flussmündungen und Marschland. Alle diese Landschaften sind ein geologisches Zeugnis der Vergangenheit der Halbinsel und jede von ihnen beherbergt unterschiedliche Lebensformen, die zum Gleichgewicht der natürlichen Welt beitragen.

programme.title: Asiens tödlichste Schlangen
programme.desc: Der Giftforscher Bryan Fry durchreist ganz Asien von den Laboratorien in Singapur bis in den Dschungel von Indien auf der Suche nach Giftschlangen mit dem Ziel, den perfekten Killer in Asien zu identifizieren.

programme.title: Kourou: Palmen, Raketen, Gefängnisinseln
programme.desc: Planet Weltweit: Lange war Französisch-Guayana an der Küste Südamerikas ein Schreckensort für Gefangene. Die Zuchthäuser dort galten als die härtesten Frankreichs. Heute sind von ihnen nur noch Ruinen übrig, die restauriert werden. Frankreich beginnt, dieses dunkle Kapitel seiner Geschichte aufzuarbeiten, nur einige Kilometer entfernt vom Weltraumbahnhof Kourou.

programme.title: Die Minenratten von Tansania
programme.desc: Im Forschungszentrum der Organisation APOPO in Tansania herrscht helle Aufregung: Eine Rattenmutter hat Junge geworfen - ein Riesenerfolg bei in Gefangenschaft lebenden Riesenhamsterratten. Schnell zeigt sich, dass einer der Rattenjungen besonders aufgeweckt ist. Er bekommt den Namen Ronaldinho. In nur wenigen Wochen lernt das intelligente Tier gefährliches TNT zu erschnüffeln.

programme.title: Montenegro
programme.desc: Planet Weltweit: Noch vor wenigen Jahren waren Esel in Montenegro vom Aussterben bedroht. Dass es die treuen Helfer noch immer gibt, ist vor allem Darko Savelji¿ zu verdanken. 2015 rettete der Biologe die erste, in elenden Verhältnissen gehaltene Eselstute. Kurze Zeit später nahm er zwei andere Esel zu sich, die als Futter für Jagdhunde geschlachtet werden sollten.

programme.title: Zuflucht in den Anden
programme.desc: Planet Weltweit: Am Tag arbeiten sie hart wie Männer. Am Abend verwandeln sie sich in das, als was sie sich fühlen: in Frauen. In ihren Gemeinden wurden sie verachtet und verstoßen. Auf den Kaffeeplantagen der kolumbianischen Anden, haben sie ein Refugium gefunden. Die Gemeinschaft von Transfrauen muss bis heute um ihre Anerkennung kämpfen

programme.title: Die Schweizergarde
programme.desc: Planet Weltweit: Seit 1506 schützt die Schweizergarde den Papst und seine Residenz. Verändert haben sich jedoch die Methoden und das Umfeld der Elitetruppe. In der traditionellen Renaissance-Uniform steckt heute ein junger, moderner und gut ausgebildeter Schweizer, der bereit ist, sein Leben für die Sicherheit des Papstes zu geben.

programme.title: Die Sonnenmenschen von Tokelau
programme.desc: Drei einsame Atolle mitten im Pazifik, die zu Pionieren in Sachen Energieerzeugung wurden: Tokelau ist die erste Nation der Welt, die ihre Stromproduktion zu 100 Prozent auf Solarenergie umgestellt hat.

programme.title: Indien
programme.desc: Planet Weltweit: Indien, das Land der Spiritualität. Heiler und Gurus, sogenannte Babas, berufen sich auf höhere Mächte. Doch es gibt Widerstand gegen den gefährlichen Aberglauben und die Geschäftemacherei mit der oft verzweifelten Hoffnung auf Gesundheit. Rationalisten touren mit ihrem Science-Van im Dienst der Wissenschaft durch das Land und klären auf.

programme.desc: Las extraordinarias vidas de la actriz Meghan Markle y el príncipe Harry. Con los mismos intereses, el príncipe Harry y Meghan Markle parecen encajar a la perfección. Ambos se han enfrentado a una educación difícil y han triunfado. Ahora triunfan juntos. Este especial de una hora, que incluye una entrevista con el biógrafo Andrew Morton, investiga el trasfondo social que hace que este matrimonio aventurero parezca totalmente acorde con la moderna Familia Real británica. Explora las extraordinarias vidas de la actriz Meghan Markle, una poderosa defensora de los derechos de la mujer, y del Príncipe Harry, que ha roto con la camisa de fuerza real sin perder su dignidad real. Ochenta y dos años después de que un romance con una plebeya divorciada de Estados Unidos condujera a la abdicación de un Rey, este matrimonio real establece y confirma un revolucionario conjunto de valores británicos.

programme.title: 바다가 만든 한 그릇. 통영 너물비빔밥
programme.desc: 자료 제공 : 국가유산청, 국가유산진흥원, 국가유산채널다양한 지역에 전통 비빔밥이 있지만 통영의 비빔밥은 생김새부터 남다릅니다. 제사 음식에서 비롯했기 때문인지 두부탕국을 곁들이는데요. 또한 해조류가 매우 풍부해 생미역과 톳나물을 비빔밥의 주재료로 이용합니다. 이외에도 계절에 따라 오이, 박, 미나리, 쑥갓 등 10가지 이상의 나물을 넣어 만든 통영의 풍성한 향토음식을 ASMR로 만나보세요. (이상희 / 전통음식문화연구가)

programme.title: 소리의 맥을 잇다, 대금장
programme.desc: 자료 제공 : 국가유산청, 국가유산진흥원, 국가유산채널대금은 대나무에 구멍을 뚫어 소리를 내는 관악기로, 옛 사대부들의 풍류를 상징하는 한국의 대표적인 전통악기 중 하나입니다. 대금 제작자들은 스스로 악기를 연주할 수 있는 대금 연주자이기도 한데요. 실제 연주자로서도 활발하게 활동하며 대금장으로서 전통의 맥을 잇고 있는 장인의 작업과정을 따라가 보시죠.(이정대 / 인천광역시 무형문화재 대금장 보유자)

programme.title: 시간이 만들어내는 명작. 먹(Meok)
programme.desc: 자료 제공 : 국가유산청, 국가유산진흥원, 국가유산채널먹은 예로부터 선비의 친구 문방사우(먹, 종이, 붓, 벼루) 중 하나로 우리의 뛰어난 기록문화유산들을 만드는 중요한 소재였습니다. 소나무를 태워 만든 연기 속에서 얻은 그을음에 아교를 넣어 먹 반죽을 만들고, 형틀에 넣어 먹을 제조하는 송연먹을 제작하는 과정을 함께 감상해봅시다. (한상묵 / 전통 먹장 숙련기술자)

programme.title: 어부, 늪의 소리를 담다. 우포늪
programme.desc: 우포늪엔 얼마만큼의 시간이 흘렀을까, 강물이 내어준 곳에 자연이 들어차고 그 주인으로 온갖 생명들이 살고 있습니다. 보이지 않지만 무수한 분초가 흐르듯 우포늪의 계절이 흐르는 소리는 신비롭죠. 들리나요? 보일듯 보이지 않는 무수한 반짝거림. 일렁임. 찰랑거림. 그 모든 시간의 자연이 조화롭게 돌아가는 소리. ※ 경상남도 창녕군 우포늪 (천연기념물 제524호)자료 제공 : 국가유산청, 국가유산진흥원, 국가유산채널

programme.title: 조선 도예의 맥을 잇다. 사기장
programme.desc: 자료 제공 : 국가유산청, 국가유산진흥원, 국가유산채널백산 가문은 조선 영조시대 이래 300여년이 넘는 세월 동안 전통 도자기의 명맥을 이어오고 있습니다. 7대 김정옥 사기장은 아들이자 전수조교 김경식 그리고 손자이자 전수생인 김지훈과 함께 9대에 걸쳐 조선왕실 도예의 계보를 잇고 있는데요. 흙, 불, 그리고 사람이 빚어낸 그릇이 섭씨 1300도 장작 가마 속에서 견딘 후 일상으로 다가오는 과정을 감상해보세요. (김정옥 / 국가무형문화재 사기장 보유자)

programme.title: 소박하지만 구수한 맛. 메밀국수
programme.desc: 자료 제공 : 국가유산청, 국가유산진흥원, 국가유산채널척박한 땅에서도 쑥쑥 자라나는 메밀이라는 곡식이 가진 특성은 강한 생존력과 함께 강원도 정선의 토속성을 느낄 수 있는 음식입니다. 전통적인 방법으로 메밀국수를 만들며 일상 속 삶의 애환을 담았던 정선아리랑을 현지인의 목소리로 들어봅니다. (김남기 / 강원도 무형문화재 정선아리랑 예능보유자)

programme.title: 겨울 전통 다과상. 궁중병과 겨울상
programme.desc: 자료 제공 : 국가유산청, 국가유산진흥원, 국가유산채널온돌방에 앉아 두텁두텁 두텁떡과 달달한 개성약과, 따뜻한 수정과 한잔 하고 가세요. 개성약과는 고려시대부터 만들어 먹었고, 중국까지 그 명성이 알려졌던 고급 과자로 파삭한 맛을 내는 것이 특징인데요. 단지, 열량이 좀 높다는 사실.... 그래도 추운 겨울이고 맛있으면 0칼로리! 아시죠? (박영미 / 국가무형문화재 조선왕조궁중음식 이수자)

programme.title: 그을음으로 먹을 만들다. 먹장
programme.desc: 먹은 예로부터 선비의 친구 문방사우(먹, 종이, 붓, 벼루) 중 하나로 우리의 뛰어난 기록문화유산들을 만드는 중요한 소재였습니다. 전통방식으로 만들어 지는 먹은 기름은 태워서 그을음으로 만드는 유연먹과 소나무 그을음으로 만드는 송연먹이 있습니다. '한상묵 장인'이 전통 먹가마를 이용하여 송연먹을 제작하는 과정을 함께 감상해봅시다. (한상묵 / 전통 먹장 숙련기술자)자료 제공 : 국가유산청, 국가유산진흥원, 국가유산채널

programme.title: Ray Charles & The Raelettes
programme.sub-title: Ray Charles and the Raelettes - North Sea Jazz
programme.desc: The North Sea Jazz Festival is the largest indoor music festival in the world, known globally as the event where the past, present and future of jazz are featured within three days. Next to a firm base of jazz as the festival's staple music genre, many others, such as blues, soul, funk, or hip hop, pass by. In 1980, American soul legend Ray Charles brought the Raelettes and the Ray Charles Orchestra to the North Sea Jazz Festival in The Hague. With the full force of these two groups behind him, Charles showed why throughout his storied career he has been viewed as one of the most recognizable voices in music.

programme.title: Oscar Peterson Trio, Stuff Smith & Ella Fitzgerald
programme.sub-title: O.P. Trio and E. Fitz. - Jazz At The Philharmonic
programme.desc: The Royal Concertgebouw in Amsterdam is a world-renowned concert hall, known for its first-rate acoustics. It has attracted many famous performers over the years and is one of the Netherlands' most treasured musical institutions. On May 5, 1957, jazz impresario Norman Granz presented his Jazz at the Philharmonic tour at the Concertgebouw in Amsterdam. The Canadian pianist Oscar Peterson and his trio of guitarist Herb Ellis and bassist Ray Brown are later joined by trumpeter Roy Eldridge and drummer Jo Jones. As an added attraction, American violinist Stuff Smith joins the proceedings. American singer Ella Fitzgerald, accompanied by pianist Don Abney, Ellis, Brown and Jones, hits her vocal peak in a stunning set that culminates in a jam session of It Don't Mean A Thing (If It Ain't Got That Swing) with the entire ensemble.

programme.title: Steve Gadd
programme.desc: Many of pianist Chick Corea's compositions have become jazz standards. As a member of Miles Davis' band in the late 1960s, he participated in the birth of the electric jazz fusion movement. In the 1970s, Corea founded the legendary jazz fusion group Return to Forever. Along with Herbie Hancock, McCoy Tyner and Keith Jarrett, Corea is one of the biggest modern jazz pianists. He continued musical collaborations with a diverse range of artists, exploring various musical styles. This broadcast features three performances that illustrate Chick Corea's many talents.

programme.title: Miles Davis
programme.desc: American trumpeter Miles Davis (1926-1991) was a pioneering jazz musician from the late 1940s to the late 1980s. His influence on 20th century music is hard to overstate, as he trailblazed bebop, cool jazz, hardbop, modal jazz, and electronic music. On October 11, 1964, Miles Davis performed at Teatro Dell'Arte in Milan. With tenor saxophonist Wayne Shorter, pianist Herbie Hancock, bassist Ron Carter and drummer Tony Williams, Davis performed Autumn Leaves, My Funny Valentine, All Blues, All of You, and Joshua.

programme.title: Art Farmer, Jim Hall, Steve Swallow & Pete La Roca
programme.sub-title: The Art Farmer Quartet live In England
programme.desc: Art Farmer: Live in '64 highlights an amazing one-hour concert featuring the great flugelhornist in his prime. Farmer's band includes legendary guitarist Jim Hall (fresh from Sonny Rollins' band), drummer Pete LaRoca, and Steve Swallow on bass. The legendary ensemble plays both standards and originals with ease and finesse and highlights why Farmer was considered one of the most innovative horn players in all of jazz.

programme.title: New York Hip Hop
programme.desc: New York Hip Hop is a regional subgenre of hip hop music that originated in New York City during the 1970s and recognized to have evolved first in the Bronx New York hip hop became a distinct subgenre after artists from other regions of the United States emerged with different styles. In contrast to other styles, this used complex lyrics for attentive listening rather than beats for dancing. The main components of hip hop culture from that time and still today are MCing, DJing, break dancing, and graffiti. With Public Enemy, Ice Cube and Big Daddy Kane

programme.title: John Legend
programme.desc: An artist with intellectual skills is John Legend, who studied English with a major in African American literature at the University of Pennsylvania. In college, he participated in a jazz group called Counterparts and at the time was introduced to singer Lauryn Hill, playing piano on the track 'Everything Is Everything' from the singer's first solo album. He finished college in 1999 and began composing his own songs Recorded two independent albums that were sold in their performances: 'John Stephens' (2000) and 'Live at Jimmy Uptown' (2001). He has performed on albums of singers like Alicia Key, Jay-Z and also made the album Wake Up! (2010) along with the American rap group, The Roots. His official discography includes Get Lifted (2004), Once Again (2006), Evolver (2008) and Love in the Future (2013). This presentation in London, 2014, at the Itunes Festival, manages to clean the career of this singer who besides being multitalented can be a human rights activist.

programme.title: Quatuor Ebène
programme.desc: Renowned French string quartet Quatuor Ébène marked the 250th birth anniversary of Ludwig van Beethoven (1770-1827) with a remarkable project: recording all of the great composer's sixteen string quartets. For five years, violinists Pierre Colombet and Gabriel Le Magadure, violist Marie Chilemme, and cellist Raphaël Merlin immersed themselves in Beethoven's 650 pages of sheet music. Their efforts culminated in the performance of the composer's complete repertoire for string quartet, which covers three decades of Beethoven's musical creativity, during six impressive concerts at Philharmonie de Paris in the autumn of 2020. Quatuor Ébène explored every facet of Beethoven's string quartet repertoire: from the youthful Opus 18 string quartets to the Razumovsky, Harp, and Serioso quartets (Opus 59, 74, and 95) from his middle period, and finally, the depth of his late quartets (Opus 127 to 135). This program features Quatuor Ébène performing Beethoven's String Quartet No. 3 in D major, Op. 18 No. 3 String Quartet No. 11 in F minor, Op. 95, “Quartetto Serioso” and String Quartet No. 8 in E minor, Op. 59, No. 2, "Razumovsky". This concert performance was recorded at Philharmonie de Paris on November 23, 2020.

programme.title: Matthias Goerne, Vilde Frang, Nicolas Altstaedt & Stathis Karapanos
programme.sub-title: J. S. Bach - Arias, solos, and duets
programme.desc: Baritone Matthias Goerne teams up with violinist Vilde Frang, cellist Nicolas Altstaedt, flutist Stathis Karapanos, and harpsichordist Michaela Hasselt in this program dedicated to the music of J. S. Bach. They perform baritone arias from Bach's most beautiful cantatas, as well as solo pieces and duets. On the program are Sonata No. 3 in C major for violin solo, BWV 1005 arias ‘Hier, in meines Vaters Stätte', BWV 32 and ‘Die Welt mit allen Königreichen', BWV 59 Suite No. 5 in C minor for cello solo, BWV 1011 ‘Wenn Trost und Hülf ermangeln muß', BWV 117 ‘Ja, ja, ich halte Jesum fest', BWV 157 Invention No. 7 in E minor, BWV 778 Invention in A major, BWV 783 and ‘Welt ade, ich bin dein müde', BWV 158. This performance was recorded at St. Mary's Church in Wittenberg, Germany.

programme.title: Elena Bashkirova, Juliane Banse, Emmanuel Pahud & Claudio Bohorquez
programme.desc: The extraordinarily talented pianist Elena Bashkirova has been president of the Felix Mendelssohn-Bartholdy Foundation in Leipzig since October 2020, succeeding legendary conductor Kurt Masur. In this concert at the Mendelssohn House in Leipzig, Bashkirova is joined by soprano Juliane Banse, flutist Emmanuel Pahud, cellist Claudio Bohórquez, clarinettist Karl-Heinz Steffens, and pianist Ohad Ben-Ari in a chamber music program dedicated to the music of Mendelssohn and his sister Fanny Hensel. The program opens with Mendelssohn's Piano Trio in D minor, Op. 49. This is followed by a selection of songs: Mendelssohn's Schilflied ‘Auf dem Teich, dem regungslosen', Op. 71 No. 4, and Reiselied ‘Der Herbstwind rüttelt die Bäume', Op. 34 No. 6 Hensel's Vorwurf, Op. 10 No. 2 Verlust, Op. 9 No. 10 and Sehnsucht, Op. 9 No. 7 Mendelssohn's ‘Allnächtlich im Traume seh ich dich', Op. 86 No. 4 ‘Die Liebende schreibt', Op. 86 No. 3 and Nachtlied ‘Vergangen ist der lichte Tag', Op. 71 No. 6. The program continues with Mendelssohn's Seven Songs without Words, for piano four-hands (Op. 62 Nos. 1-6, and Op. 67 No. 1), and comes to a close with Mendelssohn's Three pieces for clarinet, violoncello and piano (arr. Ernst Naumann), comprising Prelude, Op. 35 No. 4, Songs without Words, Op. 53 No. 2, and Duet, Op. 38 No. 6. This performance was recorded in November 2020.

programme.title: Herbert Blomstedt & Lucerne Festival Orchestra
programme.sub-title: Beethoven - Symphony No. 3 in E-flat major, Op. 55
programme.desc: Maestro Herbert Blomstedt makes his debut with the Lucerne Festival Orchestra at 2020's Lucerne Festival conducting Ludwig van Beethoven's celebrated Symphony No. 3 in E-flat major, Op. 55, “Eroica”. The sprightly Swedish conductor celebrated his 93rd birthday just one month before this performance. This remarkable performance was recorded at the Lucerne Culture and Congress Center (KKL), Switzerland, in August 2020.

programme.title: Costanza Principe
programme.desc: Italian classical pianist Costanza Principe (1993) started playing the piano at age 6, making her public debut at age 7. Before long she would be performing as a soloist with numerous prestigious orchestras in Italy, the UK, France, and South America. Seen here in 2021 at one of Italy's oldest extant Renaissance theatres, the gorgeous Teatro Olimpico in the northern Italian town of Vicenza, Principe performs Johann Sebastian Bach's ‘Concerto italiano' and ‘Ciaccona', as transcribed for piano by Ferruccio Busoni.

programme.title: Les Dissonances & David Grimal
programme.sub-title: Schubert - Symphony No. 8 in B minor, D. 759
programme.desc: Les Dissonances is a collective of artists founded by violinist David Grimal in 2004. The conductorless ensemble consists of musicians from the most prestigious European orchestras, international soloists, and young talents. In this performance Les Dissonances perform Franz Schubert's Symphony No. 8 in B minor, D. 759, also known as the ‘Unfinished Symphony'. Schubert started composing the work in 1822, but only completed the first two movements. The first movement, Allegro moderato, has a dark, mysterious mood, which contrasts with the beautiful second movement in E major, Andante con moto. Schubert only penned a couple of measures of the third movement, a Scherzo, in full score. It is not known why the composer never finished his symphony. Although it is not complete, it has become one of Schubert's most popular compositions. This performance was recorded at Cité de la musique in Paris, France, in 2013.

programme.title: Rainbow Reef Relaxation 1
programme.desc: Sit back, relax and enjoy the dazzling world of coral reefs in 4K you embark on a journey through some of the most vibrant underwater reefs on our blue planet - including many scenes which no longer look like this due to coral bleaching. From the cinematographer: "The footage for this film was shot over a period of some years in French Polynesia, Micronesia, Indonesia and East Timor. Unfortunately there are not that vibrant anymore today. Coral reefs have suffered from the rise of water temperature, rise in acidity, destructive fishing methods and severe storms caused by climate change." - Peter Schneider. "Rainbow Reef Relaxation" is a 3-hour long, sweeping yet majestic & vibrant underwater journey to the world's most beautiful lagoons, as captured by Nature Relaxation collaborator Peter Schneider (Underwatercam) paired with ambient underwater sounds and brand new ambient music by the Cynic Project. Filmed in High Definition several years ago, thanks to its age this film offers magical glimpses of an underwater world that is bursting with life, color, and beauty.

programme.title: Turtle Paradise 2
